11/13  A simplified equation to capture the idea: 
 
Real yield = Total Revenue – Operation Costs – Value of Total Token Emissions

10/13 The core idea behind real yield it all boils down to whether the protocol is profitable or not. Even with token emissions, the rewarded APY will remain sustainable as long as revenue > token supply.
9/13 The revenue can come in many forms; trading fees, swapping fees, interest rate fees, etc.

8/13 However, a new narrative surrounding real yields and “ponzi” anti-thesis has emerged within DeFi. 

Real yield focuses on the protocol’s revenue in mainstream assets such as $USDC or $BNB, holders can earn a share by staking/locking the protocol’s governance tokens.

7/13 When the bear market hit, the selling pressure from the general markets de-risking + inflating token supply caused a massive downward spiral in token prices, which ultimately fuelled the “crypto is a ponzi” narrative.

6/13 Example:

In 2021: John stakes 1 Token X which he bought at $1, APY is 100%.

In 2022: Given the APY of 100% John now has 2 Token X. However, the price of Token X decreased to $0.10. Even though he has more Token X, he made a $0.80 loss in dollar value.

5/13 This is also how some protocols can have over 1000% APY; by simply inflating their own token X supply. Due to the attractive APYs, token emissions have often been the strategy to attract demand and attention from users.
4/13 Token emission can come in many forms, essentially, it means to increase the supply of a protocol’s native token X.

3/13 Yields can come in 2 forms: 

⚡️Token emissions
⚡️Revenue generation
